%I A395254 #58 May 01 2026 23:39:17
%S A395254 2,3,5,5,13,139,1571,7193,90709,129593,3628789,43545589,1334361593,
%T A395254 40236134387,75442751987,2816529407987,193535806463983,
%U A395254 1318135762943983
%N A395254 Smallest prime p such that (q^2 - p^2) is divisible by n!, where q is the next prime after p, and -1 if no such number exists.
%C A395254 From _David A. Corneth_, Apr 20 2026: (Start)
%C A395254 a(19)..a(21) <= 32750603956223987, 143111882833919983, 23291458931220479983 respectively.
%C A395254 We have q^2 - p^2 = (q - p)*(q + p). As p < q are consecutive primes, to some extend the largest values for q-p can be found using A002386 for primes (lower end) with record gaps to the next consecutive prime and record gaps between primes respectively.
%C A395254 At the moment of writing A002386 has 84 terms in the b-file. For primes <= A002386(84) = 68068810283234182907 we have the largest gap being A005250(84) = 1764.
%C A395254 So up to that prime we can say q-p <= 1784, p+q <= 2*q and so (q-p)*(q+p) <= 1784*2*q were at some point we have a value for q and so an upper limit for (q-p)*(q+p) = q^2 - p^2 = k*n! for some k. Using this a(16)..a(18) could be verified. (End)
%F A395254 prime(A394630(n)) <= a(n).
%F A395254 A394631(n) <= a(n).
%e A395254 149 is the next prime after 139 and 149^2 - 139^2 = 2880 = 4 * 6!, and no lesser prime has this property, so a(6) = 139.
%o A395254 (PARI) a(n,pmin=2)=my(f=n!,p=pmin,q=nextprime(p+1));while(Mod(q-p,f)*Mod(p+q,f)!=0,p=q;q=nextprime(q+2));p
%o A395254 data(nmax)=my(pmin=2);for(n=1,nmax,my(x=a(n,pmin));print1(x,", ");pmin=x)
%Y A395254 Cf. A000040, A000142, A002386, A005250, A192434, A394629, A394630, A394631.
%K A395254 nonn,more,new
%O A395254 1,1
%A A395254 _Jean-Marc Rebert_, Apr 17 2026
%E A395254 a(16)-a(18) from _David A. Corneth_, Apr 20 2026
